# in the name of allah, the beneficent, the most merciful project's
~~summary this research project represents the preponderating opinions of
~~imam az-zarkashi in the field of quranic sciences as stated in his
~~published works. they were comparatively examined against the sayings of
~~the scholars throughout the scholarly books so as to attain, by allah's
~~leave, the closest saying to what is correct as well as the most
~~preponderant in light of the textual proofs. the project is comprised
~~of an introduction, preface, two parts, conclusion, and indexes. the
~~introduction included the subject's importance, reasons for its choice,
~~goals, extent of coverage, relevant previous studies, research plan and
~~methodology. the preface contained a biography of imam az-zarkashi,
~~rahimahullaah (may allaah's mercy be upon him) which included his name,
~~lineage, nickname, surname, birth place, upraising, knowledge seeking,
~~most famous of his shoyoukh (scholars), his students, his scholarly
~~rank, praise by scholars, madh-hab (school of jurisprudence), creed,
~~publications, and his death. this was followed by the first part-the
~~theoretical aspect of az-zarkashi's tarjeeh (preponderance) in the field
~~of quranic sciences. this comprised a preface, and two chapters. the
~~preface contained the following: PageV02P0080
# first: the linguistic and technical definitions of tarjeeh and the
~~relationship between them. linguistically, tarjeeh, is centered on the
~~meanings: exceeding another, firmness and soundness, and overweighing.
~~technically, however, it means giving weight (strength) to either sign
~~over the other by way of that which is not apparent. as to the tarjeeh
~~of az-zarkashi it refers to his strengthening of one saying,
~~particularly in the quran sciences, based upon a specific daleel
~~(evidence). the daleel may include all that which gives strength to the
~~preponderating opinion whether it is from the quran, as-sunnah, aathaar
~~(reports), or reasoning based upon the foundations of the sharee'ah
~~(legislations) second: his methodology in presenting the sayings and
~~rejecting the opponent's view. in most cases, this included his concern
~~with accurate quotations, non-bigoted interest in madh-hab ash-
~~shaafi'ee, mention of the evidences even of those with opposite views,
~~giving preponderance to the overweighing opinion and stating the reason
~~for his choice and avoiding attacks against the opponent. rather, he
~~refutes the opposite opinion with proof and clear reasoning.
~~PageV02P0081
# third: his influence on those after him. amongst those who benefited
~~from az-zarkashi were: (i) as-siyouti in his "itqaan" where he immensely
~~benefited from him. and so did ibn 'aqeelah in his "az-ziyaadah wal
~~ihsaan," ad-dimyaati in "al-ithaaf," al-alloousi in his "tafseer," az-
~~zarqaani in "manaahil al-'irfaan." in addition to those who came after
~~the aforementioned from the contemporary scholars who authored in the
~~field of quranic sciences whereby they benefited greatly from az-
~~zarkashi's "al-burhaan," and as-siyouti's "al-itqaan." as to the first
~~chapter, it was concerned with the terms of az-zarkhashi's tarjeeh. this
~~included the following: (a) the kinds of tarjeeh terms and their
~~denotations. for example, some of the terms he used: as-saheeh (the
~~valid), as-sawaab (the correct), ar-raajih (the preponderating), al-haq
~~(the true), at-tahqeeq (the verification), al-mu'tabar (the deemed), al-
~~mukhtaar (the chosen), al-asah (the more valid), al-qareeb (the close),
~~al-aqrab (the most close), and much more. (b) the reason for
~~diversification of tarjeeh terms. the following were some of the
~~reasons: -the preponderating saying was supported by explicit evidences
~~while that of the opponent were either not strong or very weak. this
~~prompted him to use suitable terms like as-saheeh and as-sawaab and the
~~like. PageV02P0082
# - he was unaware of the sayings of the scholars regarding a specific
~~issue, and thus it was inevitable to think and investigate by way of
~~evidence-based deduction. that is why you find him stating his tarjeeh
~~using un-explicit terms because of the possibility that the two sayings
~~are applicable to the case or issue of interest. -the issue being an
~~easy matter such as there is no blame of adopting either opinion and
~~accordingly it was suitable to use a term that accompanies such cases
~~like "al-awlaa" (more appropriate). - other reasons. where appropriate,
~~an example on each reason was incorporated the second chapter dealt
~~with az-zarkashi's aspects of tarjeeh. they were based upon the
~~indications by: (i) the quran (ii) the sunnah (iii) the aathar (reports
~~form the companions and/or the salaf) (iv) the language (v) the sayings
~~of verifying scholars. (vi) consensus (vii) the position of the salaf
~~(viii) the context (ix) the sayings of the majority opinion of the
~~scholars an example on each aspect was included. this was followed by
~~the second part-the practical aspect of az-zarkashi's tarjeeh
~~(preponderance) in the field of quranic sciences. it was collected from
~~his printed works. PageV02P0083
# the plan for the ordering of the issues of quranic sciences was based
~~upon az-zarkashi's ordering method which he used in his book al-burhaan,
~~combining some of the similar issues where needed. the issues were
~~preceded by definitions or clarifications in case of ambiguity, in
~~addition to explanations and determinations of point(s) of conflict
~~regarding each issue. this was followed by the scholarly opinions on
~~each issue, naming the scholars with their statements. after that the
~~tarjeeh of az-zarkashi was introduced in a sufficiently clear way
~~accompanied, in most cases, by his daleel or rational. the position of
~~az-zarkashi was then studied in a comparative way with those of the
~~other sayings and their respective evidences. the results of the
~~comparisons were then put together with the preponderating opinion
~~regarding each issue. these issues covered the various kinds of quranic
~~sciences such as the reasons for revelations, occasions, the madinite
~~and makkite revelations, first revealed texts, the manner of revelation,
~~the collection of the quran, its divisions, order, names, chapters'
~~names, recitation science, stop and start marking positions in quranic
~~recitations, knowledge of writing inscriptions, the preferable and the
~~excellent in the quran, etiquettes of recitation, rulings, abrogation,
~~clear and not-entirely clear (to some), miraculous standing of the
~~quran, principles of tafseer, ways and styles of addressing statements
~~in the quran, and so forth. PageV02P0084
# after that a conclusion of the main results of this investigation, as
~~well as the related recommendations, was included. at last a set of
~~indexes was made: (i) quranic verses (ii) prophetic narrations and
~~reports (iii) biographies of the eminent and distinguished (iv) places
~~and countries (v) preponderated issues (vi) sources and references, and
~~(vii) subjects all praise is due to allah, and it is by his favor,
~~subhaanahu wa ta'aala (the one free of all imperfection, the most high),
~~that this project was concluded. the investigator: PageV02P0085